The article is about commemorating the Meds Yeghern, also known as the Armenian Genocide, which took place during the final years of the Ottoman Empire. It highlights the deportation, massacre, and death of one and a half million Armenians. The author joins the Armenian community in mourning the loss of innocent lives and acknowledges the resilience of the Armenian people who built new lives in the United States. The article emphasizes the importance of remembering atrocities to prevent them from happening again and welcomes efforts by Turks and Armenians to acknowledge and reconcile with the painful history for a more just and tolerant future.